      "question": "If $\\cos \\theta + \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\cos \\theta$, then the value of $\\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta$ is",
      "answer": "(B)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Square both sides of the given equation $\\cos \\theta + \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\cos \\theta$.",
          "Expand the left side to get $\\cos^2 \\theta + \\sin^2 \\theta + 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 2 \\cos^2 \\theta$.",
          "Use the identity $\\sin^2 \\theta + \\cos^2 \\theta = 1$ to rewrite the equation as $1 + 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 2 \\cos^2 \\theta$.",
          "Rearrange to find $2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta = 2 \\cos^2 \\theta - 1$.",
          "Let $x = \\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta$. Square $x$ to get $x^2 = \\cos^2 \\theta + \\sin^2 \\theta - 2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta$.",
          "Substitute $1$ for $\\cos^2 \\theta + \\sin^2 \\theta$ and $(2 \\cos^2 \\theta - 1)$ for $2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta$.",
          "Calculate $x^2 = 1 - (2 \\cos^2 \\theta - 1) = 2 - 2 \\cos^2 \\theta = 2 \\sin^2 \\theta$.",
          "Since $\\cos \\theta + \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\cos \\theta$, then $\\sin \\theta = (\\sqrt{2} - 1) \\cos \\theta$. Thus $\\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta = \\cos \\theta - (\\sqrt{2} - 1) \\cos \\theta = (2 - \\sqrt{2}) \\cos \\theta$. Evaluating the square root gives $\\sqrt{2} \\sin \\theta$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\cos \\theta + \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\cos \\theta \\Rightarrow \\sin \\theta = (\\sqrt{2}-1) \\cos \\theta \\\\ \\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta = \\cos \\theta - (\\sqrt{2}-1) \\cos \\theta \\\\ = \\cos \\theta (1 - \\sqrt{2} + 1) = (2 - \\sqrt{2}) \\cos \\theta \\\\ \\text{Using } \\sin \\theta = (\\sqrt{2}-1) \\cos \\theta \\text{ in } \\sqrt{2} \\sin \\theta \\\\ = \\sqrt{2}(\\sqrt{2}-1) \\cos \\theta = (2 - \\sqrt{2}) \\cos \\theta \\\\ \\therefore \\cos \\theta - \\sin \\theta = \\sqrt{2} \\sin \\theta$"
      },
